# Agent Discipline

## Before Non-Trivial Changes

- Restate what you're about to do and why before making changes
- If changing more than 3 files, list them first and wait for acknowledgment
- For spec-driven work, reference the spec slug and phase

## "Done" Means Proven

- Verification commands must pass (detect from project: package.json, Makefile, Cargo.toml, pyproject.toml, go.mod)
- When claiming "tests pass" — cite the command run and exit code
- When claiming "deploy works" — cite the URL checked and HTTP status
- When claiming "bug is fixed" — cite reproduction steps and verification output
- When claiming a domain fact — cite the source file and line

## Escalation

- If stuck after 3 attempts at the same problem, stop and report what you've tried
- Never delete user files without explicit permission
- Never skip verification steps
- If a spec exists for the current work, read it before making changes

## Context Rotation

- If the session has been running for a long time and responses are getting less precise, suggest a handoff: "This session is getting long. Want me to create a /handoff so a fresh session can continue with full context?"
- Always prefer writing findings to specs/ over keeping them only in chat
- When investigating, record evidence in specs/<slug>/research.md rather than only narrating it

## Parallel Agent Discipline

When spawning parallel sub-agents:
- Each agent gets a fixed spec, a fixed set of files, and exit-code success criteria
- Do not run parallel agents on overlapping file sets
- Prefer narrow, bounded tasks: "verify this specific function works" over "improve the module"
